data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with proper MSTest collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**What changed:**

| Original | Replacement | Why |
|----------|-------------|-----|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Clearer failure message: "Expected non-empty collection" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows expected vs actual count on failure |
| `.Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Asserts exactly one match and returns it |

The `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` is fine to keep — there's no built-in "all match predicate" assertion in MSTest. If it fails, consider adding a descriptive message:

```csharp
Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
```
